Introduction 
The purpose of this Product Requirements Document is to outline the specifications for Project 
Pokédex, an interactive and nostalgic web application. The application leverages advanced AI 
and Cloud computing capabilities to deliver a fast and feature rich card collecting application. 
Objective 
The primary objective is to continue the development and deliver the final product of the 
Pokédex project, employ further applications of AI and machine learning for increased 
performance, accessibility, and interactivity with the user. We will continue to support and 
develop the core features of the application as well which provide information about Pokémon 
and One Piece trading cards including trade value, set details, meta data, and card game utility. 
System Description 
Project Pokédex is an interactive web application that utilizes machine learning, and cloud 
computing solutions to scan, analyze, and deliver valuable information with a more interactive 
card collection experience than the current market. The system is built as a modular web 
platform consisting of 4 primary layers: the frontend interface, backend services, machine 
learning engine, and data storage infrastructure. 
1. Frontend (User Interface) 
The frontend is a responsive web interface optimized for mobile and tablet devices. It 
allows users to scan cards via their device camera, view card details, manage their profile, 
and access a personal library of past scans and collected cards. Accessibility is a core 
focus — all UI components will meet WCAG 2.1 compliance. 
2. Backend (Application Server): 
The backend is composed of 3 major cloud services. AWS DynamoDG for database 
selection. AWS Lambda will deliver on user authentication, API requisition, and web 
server hosting. Vertex AI, for Generative AI application. With these tools users can gain 
access to relevant metadata, such as card value, set number, and trading details, from a 
central card database, have application access with any online device, and expect quick 
and responsive interactive features with a dedicated API host to query faster than any 
standard consumer local machine.  
3. Machine Learning Engine: 
At the heart of Project Pokédex is the image recognition module. This core feature can 
scan and deliver on pertinent information on any card in the Pokémon Trading Card 
Game (TCG) Scarlet and Violet Series as well as the One Piece TCG. The model is 
trained on a comprehensive dataset of Pokémon Trading Cards and One Piece TCG 
images to identify cards with at least 90% accuracy and determine their trade value based 
on card condition and status (surface imperfections, foil quality, rarity, etc.). The engine 
provides classification results, which are then paired with additional metadata and relayed 
to the user. 
4. Data Storage & User Profiles: 
User data is securely stored in cloud storage solutions hosted and maintained by AWS 
DynamoDB. Each user’s scan library allows them to revisit previous identifications, view 
trends, and organize their collection. All personal data follows best practices in 
encryption and storage security. 
5. Audio Interaction Layer (AI Voice Interlude): 
A lightweight audio subsystem powered with Google cloud’s VertexAI provides dynamic 
voice feedback for scans to emulate the classic anime experience. This component 
utilizes VertexAI to convert a card synopsis into spoken feedback, making the app more 
accessible and immersive. 
6. System Architecture Overview: 
The architecture follows a client-server model, where the client (web app user) 
communicates with backend APIs on AWS DynamoDB to handle authentication, data 
retrieval, and ML inference requests. The ML model will be hosted on our local machine 
as an API that the webpage can use. 
High-Level Flow: 
1. The user opens the web app and logs in using a mobile device of their choice. 
2. The user scans a Pokémon or One Piece card using the camera. 
3. The image is sent to the backend for preprocessing and ML inference. 
4. The ML model identifies the card and returns metadata. 
5. The backend fetches supplementary details (trade value, set, etc.). 
6. The frontend displays results and delivers real time generative vocal feedback. 
7. The scan and metadata are stored in the user’s profile for future access. 
